# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ground-station-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In radio-frequency engineering, an **antenna** (American English) or **aerial** (British English) is a structure used to convert alternating electric currents into radio waves for transmission, and to convert radio waves back into electric currents for reception.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It is the interface between radio waves propagating through space and electric currents moving in metal conductors, used with a transmitter or receiver.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In transmission, a radio transmitter supplies an electric current to the antenna's terminals, and the antenna radiates the energy from the current as electromagnetic waves (radio waves).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In reception, an antenna intercepts some of the power of a radio wave in order to produce an electric current at its terminals, that is applied to a receiver to be amplified.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are essential components of all radio equipment.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna is an array of conductor segments (elements), electrically connected to the receiver or transmitter.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be designed to transmit and receive radio waves in all horizontal directions equally (omnidirectional antennas), or preferentially in a particular direction (directional, or high-gain, or "beam" antennas).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna may include components not connected to the transmitter, parabolic reflectors, horns, or parasitic elements, which serve to direct the radio waves into a beam or other desired radiation pattern.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Strong directivity and good transmitting efficiency when transmitting are hard to achieve with antennas whose dimensions are much smaller than a half wavelength.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The first antennas were built in 1886 by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in his pioneering experiments to prove the existence of electromagnetic waves predicted by the 1867 electromagnetic theory of James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Hertz placed dipole antennas at the focal point of parabolic reflectors for both transmitting and receiving.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Starting in 1895, Guglielmo Marconi began development of antennas practical for long-distance wireless telegraphy and opened a factory in Chelmsford, England, to manufacture his invention in 1898.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] antenna receiving a radio wave: The electric field (E) of the wave excites oscillating currents (black arrows) in the receiver.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna radiating radio waves: The transmitter applies an alternating current (red arrows) to the rods, which charges them alternately positive and negative, emitting loops of electric field.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The arrows of the loops get reversed each time the current changes polarity.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The words *antenna* and *aerial* are used interchangeably.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Occasionally the equivalent term "aerial" is used to specifically mean an elevated horizontal wire antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The origin of the word *antenna* relative to wireless apparatus is attributed to Italian radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In the summer of 1895, Marconi began testing his wireless system outdoors on his father's estate near Bologna and soon began to experiment with long wire "aerials" suspended from a pole.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In Italian a tent pole is known as *l'antenna centrale*, and the pole with the wire was simply called *l'antenna*.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Until then wireless radiating transmitting and receiving elements were known simply as "terminals".
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Because of his prominence, Marconi's use of the word *antenna* spread among wireless researchers and enthusiasts, and later to the general public.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are required by any radio receiver or transmitter to couple its electrical connection to the electromagnetic field.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Radio waves are electromagnetic waves that carry signals through space at the speed of light; in free space they propagate without material absorption, apart from geometric spreading loss.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be classified as omnidirectional, radiating energy approximately equally in all horizontal directions, or directional, where radio waves are concentrated in some direction(s).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A so-called beam antenna is *unidirectional* – designed for maximum response in the direction of the remote station they are aligned with – whereas many other antennas are intended to respond to stations in several directions, but are not truly omnidirectional.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Since antennas obey *reciprocity*, the same radiation pattern applies both to transmission as well as reception of radio waves.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A hypothetical antenna that radiates equally in all directions (vertical as well as all horizontal angles) is called an *isotropic radiator*; however, *exact* uniformity cannot be accomplished in practical antennas, and is only rarely desired (e.g. emergency antennas for spacecraft).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Rather, for most terrestrial communications, there is an advantage in *reducing* radiation toward the sky or ground in favor of horizontal direction(s).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Several dipole elements of slightly different lengths can be stacked in parallel, into an antenna array such as the Yagi–Uda in order to focus their radiation into a single horizontal direction, perpendicular to the stack, thus termed a *beam antenna*.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole antenna is a balanced element, with equal and opposite voltages and currents at its two terminals, and serves as a simple reference for analyzing many other antenna designs.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The vertical antenna is a *monopole* antenna, not balanced with respect to ground.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The ground (or any large conductive surface) plays the role of the second conductor of a monopole.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Since monopole antennas rely on a conductive surface, they may be mounted with a *ground plane* to approximate the effect of being mounted on the Earth's surface.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] More complex antennas increase the directivity of the antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Additional elements in the antenna structure, which need not be directly connected to the receiver or transmitter, increase its directionality.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna "gain" describes the concentration of radiated power into a particular solid angle of space.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifier gain, which generally implies a net increase in signal power, antenna gain reflects a redistribution of power so that more is radiated in some directions and less in others, without increasing the total radiated power.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifiers, antennas are electrically "passive" devices which conserve total power, and there is no increase in total power above that delivered from the power source (the transmitter), only improved distribution of that fixed total.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A phased array consists of two or more simple antennas which are connected together through an electrical network.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This often involves a number of parallel dipole antennas with a certain spacing.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Depending on the relative phase introduced by the network, the same combination of dipole antennas can operate as a "broadside array" (directional normal to a line connecting the elements) or as an "end-fire array" (directional along the line connecting the elements).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna arrays may employ any basic (omnidirectional or weakly directional) antenna type, such as dipole, loop or slot antennas.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Log‑periodic and other frequency‑independent antennas employ self‑similar structures in order to operate effectively over a wide range of frequencies (i.e., with wide bandwidth).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The most familiar example is the log-periodic dipole array which can be seen as a number (typically 10 to 20) of connected dipole elements with progressive lengths in an endfire array making it rather directional; it finds use especially as a rooftop antenna for television reception.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, a Yagi–Uda antenna (or simply "Yagi"), with a somewhat similar appearance, has only one dipole element with an electrical connection; the other parasitic elements interact with the electromagnetic field in order to realize a highly directional antenna but with a narrow bandwidth.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Even greater directionality can be obtained using *aperture antennas* such as the parabolic reflector or horn antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Since high directivity in an antenna depends on it being large compared to the wavelength, highly directional antennas (thus with high antenna gain) become more practical at higher frequencies (UHF and above).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] At low frequencies (such as AM broadcast), arrays of vertical towers are used to achieve directionality and they will occupy large areas of land.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For reception, a long Beverage antenna can have significant directivity.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For non directional portable use, a short vertical antenna or small loop antenna works well, with the main design challenge being that of impedance matching.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] With a vertical antenna a *loading coil* at the base of the antenna may be employed to cancel the reactive component of impedance; small loop antennas are tuned with parallel capacitors for this purpose.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna *lead-in* is the transmission line, or feed line, that connects the antenna to a transmitter or receiver.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The "antenna feed" may refer to all components connecting the antenna to the transmitter or receiver, such as an impedance matching network in addition to the transmission line.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A microwave antenna may also be fed directly from a waveguide in place of a (conductive) transmission line.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna counterpoise, or ground plane, is a structure of conductive material which improves or substitutes for the ground.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It may be connected to or insulated from the natural ground.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In a monopole antenna, this aids in the function of the natural ground, particularly where variations (or limitations) of the characteristics of the natural ground interfere with its proper function.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Such a structure is normally connected to the return connection of an unbalanced transmission line such as the shield of a coaxial cable.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An electromagnetic wave refractor in some aperture antennas is a component which due to its shape and position functions to selectively delay or advance portions of the electromagnetic wavefront passing through it.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The refractor alters the spatial characteristics of the wave on one side relative to the other side.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It can, for instance, bring the wave to a focus or alter the wave front in other ways, generally in order to maximize the directivity of the antenna system.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This is the radio equivalent of an optical lens.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna coupling network is a passive network (generally a combination of inductive and capacitive circuit elements) used for impedance matching in between the antenna and the transmitter or receiver.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This may be used to minimize losses on the feed line, by reducing transmission line's standing wave ratio, and to present the transmitter or receiver with a standard resistive impedance needed for its optimum operation.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The feed point location(s) is selected, and antenna elements electrically similar to tuner components may be incorporated in the antenna structure itself, to improve the match.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It is a fundamental property of antennas that most of the electrical characteristics of an antenna, such as those described in the next section (e.g. gain, radiation pattern, impedance, bandwidth, resonant frequency and polarization), are the same whether the antenna is transmitting or receiving.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This equivalence follows reciprocity theorem of electromagnetics.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, in discussions of antenna properties no distinction is usually made between receiving and transmitting terminology, and the antenna can be viewed as either transmitting or receiving, whichever is more convenient.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A necessary condition for the aforementioned reciprocity property is that the materials in the antenna and transmission medium are linear and reciprocal.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] *Reciprocal* (or *bilateral*) means that the material has the same response to an electric current or magnetic field in one direction, as it has to the field or current in the opposite direction.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Most materials used in antennas meet these conditions, but some microwave antennas use high-tech components such as isolators and circulators, made of nonreciprocal materials such as ferrite.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] These can be used to give the antenna a different behavior on receiving than it has on transmitting, which can be useful in applications like radar.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The majority of antenna designs are based on the *resonance* principle.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This relies on the behaviour of moving electrons, which reflect off surfaces where the dielectric constant changes, in a fashion similar to the way light reflects when optical properties change.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In these designs, the reflective surface is created by the end of a conductor, normally a thin metal wire or rod, which in the simplest case has a *feed point* at one end where it is connected to a transmission line.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The conductor, or *element*, is aligned with the electrical field of the desired signal, normally meaning it is perpendicular to the line from the antenna to the source (or receiver in the case of a broadcast antenna).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The radio signal's electric component induces a voltage in the conductor.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This causes an electrical current to begin flowing in the direction of the signal's instantaneous field.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] When the resulting current reaches the end of the conductor, it reflects, which is equivalent to a 180 degree change in phase.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] If the conductor is ⁠ 1 /4⁠ of a wavelength long, current from the feed point will undergo 90 degree phase change by the time it reaches the end of the conductor, reflect through 180 degrees, and then another 90 degrees as it travels back.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] That means it has undergone a total 360 degree phase change, returning it to the original signal.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The current in the element thus adds to the current being created from the source at that instant.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This process creates a standing wave in the conductor, with the maximum current at the feed.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The ordinary half-wave dipole is probably the most widely used antenna design.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This consists of two ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength elements arranged end-to-end, and lying along essentially the same axis (or *collinear*), each feeding one side of a two-conductor transmission wire.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The physical arrangement of the two elements places them 180 degrees out of phase, which means that at any given instant one of the elements is driving current into the transmission line while the other is pulling it out.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The monopole antenna is essentially one half of the half-wave dipole, a single ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength element with the other side connected to ground or an equivalent ground plane (or *counterpoise*).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Monopoles, which are one-half the size of a dipole, are common for long-wavelength radio signals where a dipole would be impractically large.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Another common design is the folded dipole which consists of two (or more) half-wave dipoles placed side by side and connected at their ends but only one of which is driven.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The standing wave forms with this desired pattern at the design operating frequency, fo, and antennas are normally designed to be this size.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] However, feeding that element with 3 fo (whose wavelength is ⁠ 1 /3⁠ that of fo) will also lead to a standing wave pattern.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Thus, an antenna element is *also* resonant when its length is ⁠ 3 /4⁠ of a wavelength.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This is true for all odd multiples of ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This allows some flexibility of design in terms of antenna lengths and feed points.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas used in such a fashion are known to be *harmonically operated*.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Resonant antennas usually use a linear conductor (or *element*), or pair of such elements, each of which is about a quarter of the wavelength in length (an odd multiple of quarter wavelengths will also be resonant).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas that are required to be small compared to the wavelength sacrifice efficiency and cannot be very directional.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Since wavelengths are so small at higher frequencies (UHF, microwaves) trading off performance to obtain a smaller physical size is usually not required.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The quarter-wave elements imitate a series-resonant electrical element due to the standing wave present along the conductor.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] At the resonant frequency, the standing wave has a current peak and voltage node (minimum) at the feed.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In electrical terms, this means that at that position, the element has minimum impedance magnitude, generating the maximum current for minimum voltage.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This is the ideal situation, because it produces the maximum output for the minimum input, producing the highest possible efficiency.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Contrary to an ideal (lossless) series-resonant circuit, a finite resistance remains (corresponding to the relatively small voltage at the feed-point) due to the antenna's resistance to radiating, as well as any conventional electrical losses from producing heat.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Recall that a current will reflect when there are changes in the electrical properties of the material.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This leads to the concept of impedance matching, the design of the overall system of antenna and transmission line so the impedance is as close as possible, thereby reducing these losses.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Impedance matching is accomplished by a circuit called an antenna tuner or impedance matching network between the transmitter and antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The impedance match between the feedline and antenna is measured by a parameter called the standing wave ratio (SWR) on the feedline.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Consider a half-wave dipole designed to work with signals with wavelength 1 m, meaning the antenna would be approximately 50 cm from tip to tip.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] If the element has a length-to-diameter ratio of 1000, it will have an inherent impedance of about 63 ohms resistive.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Using the appropriate transmission wire or balun, we match that resistance to ensure minimum signal reflection.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Feeding that antenna with a current of 1 Ampere will require 63 Volts, and the antenna will radiate 63 Watts (ignoring losses) of radio frequency power.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Now consider the case when the antenna is fed a signal with a wavelength of 1.25 m; in this case the current induced by the signal would arrive at the antenna's feedpoint out-of-phase with the signal, causing the net current to drop while the voltage remains the same.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Electrically this appears to be a very high impedance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna and transmission line no longer have the same impedance, and the signal will be reflected back into the antenna, reducing output.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This could be addressed by changing the matching system between the antenna and transmission line, but that solution only works well at the new design frequency.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The result is that the resonant antenna will efficiently feed a signal into the transmission line only when the source signal's frequency is close to that of the design frequency of the antenna, or one of the resonant multiples.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This makes resonant antenna designs inherently narrow-band: Only useful for a small range of frequencies centered around the resonance(s).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It is possible to use simple impedance matching techniques to allow the use of monopole or dipole antennas substantially shorter than the ⁠ 1 /4⁠ or ⁠ 1 /2⁠ wave, respectively, at which they are resonant.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Sometimes the resulting (lower) electrical resonant frequency of such a system (antenna plus matching network) is described using the concept of *electrical length*.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna operated at a lower frequency than its self‑resonant frequency is then called an *electrically short antenna*.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For example, at 30 MHz (10 m wavelength) a true resonant ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave monopole would be almost 2.5 meters long, and using an antenna only 1.5 meters tall would require the addition of a loading coil.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Then it may be said that the coil has lengthened the antenna to achieve an electrical length of 2.5 meters.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] However, the resulting resistive impedance achieved will be quite a bit lower than that of a true ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave (resonant) monopole, often requiring further impedance matching (a transformer) to the desired transmission line.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For ever shorter antennas (requiring greater "electrical lengthening") the radiation resistance plummets (approximately according to the square of the antenna length), so that the mismatch due to a net reactance away from the electrical resonance worsens.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Or one could as well say that the equivalent resonant circuit of the antenna system has a higher Q factor and thus a reduced bandwidth, which can even become inadequate for the transmitted signal's spectrum.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Resistive losses due to the loading coil, relative to the decreased radiation resistance, entail a reduced electrical efficiency, which can be of great concern for a transmitting antenna, but bandwidth is the major factor that sets the size of antennas at 1 MHz and lower frequencies.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The power flux density of the field from a transmitting antenna decreases with distance according to the inverse-square law, reflecting the geometrical spreading of the wave.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For a given incoming flux, the power captured by a receiving antenna is proportional to its *effective area*.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole, for example, has an effective area of about 0.13 λ2 when viewed from broadside.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For an already efficient antenna design, the effective area (and thus gain) in a given direction can be increased only by reducing the gain in other directions.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] If a half-wave dipole is not connected to an external circuit but rather shorted out at the feedpoint, then it becomes a resonant half-wave element which efficiently produces a standing wave in response to an impinging radio wave.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Because there is no load to absorb that power, it retransmits all of that power, possibly with a phase shift which is critically dependent on the element's exact length.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Thus such a conductor can be arranged in order to transmit a second copy of a transmitter's signal in order to affect the radiation pattern (and feedpoint impedance) of the element electrically connected to the transmitter.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna elements used in this way are known as passive radiators.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A Yagi–Uda array uses passive elements to greatly increase gain in one direction (at the expense of other directions).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A number of parallel approximately half-wave elements (of very specific lengths) are situated parallel to each other, at specific positions, along a boom; the boom is only for support and not involved electrically.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Only one of the elements is electrically connected to the transmitter or receiver, while the remaining elements are passive.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The Yagi produces a fairly large gain (depending on the number of passive elements) and is widely used as a directional antenna with an antenna rotor to control the direction of its beam.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It suffers from having a rather limited bandwidth, restricting its use to certain applications.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] What's more, a phased array can be made "steerable", that is, by changing the phases applied to each element the radiation pattern can be shifted *without* physically moving the antenna elements.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] When a radio wave hits a large conducting sheet it is reflected (with the phase of the electric field reversed) just as a mirror reflects light.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Placing such a reflector behind an otherwise non-directional antenna will insure that the power that would have gone in its direction is redirected toward the desired direction, increasing the antenna's gain by a factor of at least 2.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Likewise, a corner reflector can insure that all of the antenna's power is concentrated in only one quadrant of space (or less) with a consequent increase in gain.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Practically speaking, the reflector need not be a solid metal sheet, but can consist of a curtain of rods aligned with the antenna's polarization; this greatly reduces the reflector's weight and wind load.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Specular reflection of radio waves is also employed in a parabolic reflector antenna, in which a *curved* reflecting surface effects focussing of an incoming wave toward a so-called feed antenna; this results in an antenna system with an effective area comparable to the size of the reflector itself.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Other concepts from geometrical optics are also employed in antenna technology, such as with the lens antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's power gain (or simply "gain") also takes into account the antenna's efficiency, and is often the primary figure of merit.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are characterized by a number of performance measures which a user would be concerned with in selecting or designing an antenna for a particular application.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A plot of the directional characteristics in the space surrounding the antenna is its *radiation pattern*.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The frequency range or *bandwidth* over which an antenna functions well can be very wide (as in a log-periodic antenna) or narrow (as in a small loop antenna); outside this range the antenna impedance becomes a poor match to the transmission line and transmitter (or receiver).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Use of the antenna well away from its design frequency affects its radiation pattern, reducing its directive gain.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Generally an antenna will not have a feed-point impedance that matches that of a transmission line; a matching network between antenna terminals and the transmission line will improve power transfer to the antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A non-adjustable matching network will most likely place further limits the usable bandwidth of the antenna system.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It may be desirable to use tubular elements, instead of thin wires, to make an antenna; these will allow a greater bandwidth.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Or, several thin wires can be grouped in a *cage* to simulate a thicker element.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This widens the bandwidth of the resonance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Amateur radio antennas that operate at several frequency bands which are widely separated from each other may connect elements resonant at those different frequencies in parallel.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Most of the transmitter's power will flow into the resonant element while the others present a high impedance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Another solution uses *traps*, parallel resonant circuits which are strategically placed in breaks created in long antenna elements.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] When used at the trap's particular resonant frequency the trap presents a very high impedance (parallel resonance) effectively truncating the element at the location of the trap; if positioned correctly, the truncated element makes a proper resonant antenna at the trap frequency.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] At substantially higher or lower frequencies the trap allows the full length of the broken element to be employed, but with a resonant frequency shifted by the net reactance added by the trap.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The bandwidth characteristics of a resonant antenna element can be characterized according to its *Q* where the resistance involved is the radiation resistance, which represents the emission of energy from the resonant antenna to free space.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The *Q* of a narrow band antenna can be as high as 15.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the reactance at the same off-resonant frequency of one using thick elements is much less, consequently resulting in a *Q* as low as 5.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] These two antennas may perform equivalently at the resonant frequency, but the second antenna will perform over a bandwidth 3 times as wide as the antenna consisting of a thin conductor.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas for use over much broader frequency ranges are achieved using further techniques.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Adjustment of a matching network can, in principle, allow for any antenna to be matched at any frequency.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Thus the small loop antenna built into most AM broadcast (medium wave) receivers has a very narrow bandwidth, but is tuned using a parallel capacitance which is adjusted according to the receiver tuning.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, log-periodic antennas are *not* resonant at any single frequency but can (in principle) be built to attain similar characteristics (including feedpoint impedance) over any frequency range.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] These are therefore commonly used (in the form of directional log-periodic dipole arrays) as television antennas.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is a parameter which measures the degree of directivity of the antenna's radiation pattern.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A high-gain antenna will radiate most of its power in a particular direction, while a low-gain antenna will radiate over a wide angle.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] High-gain antennas have the advantage of longer range and better signal quality, but must be aimed carefully at the other antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a high-gain antenna is a parabolic dish such as a satellite television antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Low-gain antennas have shorter range, but the orientation of the antenna is relatively unimportant.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a low-gain antenna is the whip antenna found on portable radios and cordless phones.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna gain should not be confused with amplifier gain, a separate parameter measuring the increase in signal power due to an amplifying device placed at the front-end of the system, such as a low-noise amplifier.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The *effective area* or effective aperture of a receiving antenna expresses the portion of the power of a passing electromagnetic wave which the antenna delivers to its terminals, expressed in terms of an equivalent area.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, if a radio wave passing a given location has a flux of 1 pW / m2 (10−12 Watts per square meter) and an antenna has an effective area of 12 m2, then the antenna would deliver 12 pW of RF power to the receiver (30 microvolts RMS at 75 ohms).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Since the receiving antenna is not equally sensitive to signals received from all directions, the effective area is a function of the direction to the source.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Due to reciprocity (discussed above) the gain of an antenna used for transmitting must be proportional to its effective area when used for receiving.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Consider an antenna with no loss, that is, one whose electrical efficiency is 100%.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It can be shown that its effective area averaged over all directions must be equal to λ2/4π, the wavelength squared divided by 4π.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is defined such that the average gain over all directions for an antenna with 100% electrical efficiency is equal to 1.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For an antenna with an efficiency of less than 100%, both the effective area and gain are reduced by that same amount.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, the above relationship between gain and effective area still holds.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] These are thus two different ways of expressing the same quantity.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] *A*eff is especially convenient when computing the power that would be received by an antenna of a specified gain, as illustrated by the above example.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern of an antenna is a plot of the relative field strength of the radio waves emitted by the antenna at different angles in the far field.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It is typically represented by a three-dimensional graph, or polar plots of the horizontal and vertical cross sections.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The pattern of an ideal isotropic antenna, which radiates equally in all directions, would look like a sphere.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Many nondirectional antennas, such as monopoles and dipoles, emit equal power in all horizontal directions, with the power dropping off at higher and lower angles; this is called an omnidirectional pattern and when plotted looks like a torus or donut.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation of many antennas shows a pattern of maxima or "*lobes*" at various angles, separated by "*nulls*", angles where the radiation falls to zero.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] This is because the radio waves emitted by different parts of the antenna typically interfere, causing maxima at angles where the radio waves arrive at distant points in phase, and zero radiation at other angles where the radio waves arrive out of phase.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In a directional antenna designed to project radio waves in a particular direction, the lobe in that direction is designed larger than the others and is called the "*main lobe*".
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The other lobes usually represent unwanted radiation and are called "*sidelobes*".
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The axis through the main lobe is called the "*principal axis*" or "*boresight axis*".
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The polar radiation patterns of Yagi antennas become narrower, and their directivity (and thus gain) increases, when they are designed for a relatively narrow frequency range, as compared with wideband designs.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The space surrounding an antenna can be divided into three concentric regions: The reactive near-field (also called the inductive near-field), the radiating near-field (Fresnel region) and the far-field (Fraunhofer) regions.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] These regions are useful to identify the field structure in each, although the transitions between them are gradual; there are no clear boundaries.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The orientation and physical structure of an antenna determine the *polarization* of the electric field of the radio wave transmitted by it.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, an antenna composed of a linear conductor (such as a dipole or whip antenna) oriented vertically will result in vertical polarization; if turned on its side the same antenna's polarization will be horizontal.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In the most general case, polarization is elliptical, meaning that over each cycle the electric field vector traces out an ellipse.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Two special cases are linear polarization (the ellipse collapses into a line) as discussed above, and circular polarization (in which the two axes of the ellipse are equal).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In linear polarization the electric field of the radio wave oscillates along one direction.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In circular polarization, the electric field of the radio wave rotates around the axis of propagation.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Circular or elliptically polarized radio waves are designated as right-handed or left-handed using the "thumb in the direction of the propagation" rule.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Note that for circular polarization, optical researchers use the opposite right-hand rule from the one used by radio engineers.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] It is best for the receiving antenna to match the polarization of the transmitted wave for optimum reception.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Otherwise there will be a loss of signal strength: when a linearly polarized antenna receives linearly polarized radiation at a relative angle of θ, then there will be a power loss of cos2θ .
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] A circularly polarized antenna can be used to equally well match vertical or horizontal linear polarizations, suffering a 3 dB signal reduction.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] However it will be blind to a circularly polarized signal of the opposite orientation.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Maximum power transfer requires matching the impedance of an antenna system (as seen looking into the transmission line) to the complex conjugate of the impedance of the receiver or transmitter.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The intended impedance is normally resistive, but a transmitter (and some receivers) may have limited additional adjustments to cancel a certain amount of reactance, in order to "tweak" the match.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The match is sought to minimize the amplitude of standing waves (measured via the standing wave ratio; SWR) that a mismatch raises on the line, and the increase in transmission line losses it entails.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna tuning, in the strict sense of modifying the antenna itself, generally refers only to cancellation of any reactance seen at the antenna terminals, leaving only a resistive impedance which might or might not be exactly the desired impedance (that of the available transmission line).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Although an antenna may be designed to have a purely resistive feedpoint impedance (such as a dipole 97% of a half wavelength long) at just one frequency, this will very likely not be exactly true at other frequencies that the antenna is eventually used for.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In most cases, in principle the physical length of the antenna can be "trimmed" to obtain a pure resistance, although this is rarely convenient.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the addition of a contrary inductance or capacitance can be used to cancel a residual capacitive or inductive reactance, respectively, and may be more convenient than lowering and trimming or extending the antenna, then hoisting it back.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In addition to those reactance-neutralizing add-ons, antennas of any kind may include a transformer and / or transformer balun at their feedpoint, to change the resistive part of the impedance to more nearly match the feedline's characteristic impedance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] An additional problem is matching the remaining resistive impedance to the characteristic impedance of the transmission line: A general impedance matching network (an "antenna tuner" or ATU) will have at least two adjustable elements to correct both components of impedance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Any matching network will have both power losses and power restrictions when used for transmitting.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Commercial antennas are generally designed to approximately match standard 50 Ohm coaxial cables, at standard frequencies; the design expectation is that a matching network will be merely used to 'tweak' any residual mismatch.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] In some cases matching is done in a more extreme manner, not simply to cancel a small amount of residual reactance, but to resonate an antenna whose resonance frequency is quite different from the intended frequency of operation.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The physically large inductor at the base of the antenna has an inductive reactance which is the opposite of the capacitative reactance that the short vertical antenna has at the desired operating frequency.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] (usually, but not always, for receiving) at a relatively low frequency, where it appears almost as a pure inductor.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] to produce a better-matched feedpoint resistance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The loop is resonated by a coupled tuning capacitor, which is configured to match the receiver's tuning, in order to keep the antenna resonant at the chosen receive frequency over the AM broadcast band.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Ground reflections is one of the common types of multipath.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern and even the driving point impedance of an antenna can be influenced by the dielectric constant and especially conductivity of nearby objects.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] For a terrestrial antenna, the ground is usually one such object of importance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's height above the ground, as well as the electrical properties (permittivity and conductivity) of the ground, can then be important.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Also, in the particular case of a monopole antenna, the ground (or an artificial ground plane) serves as the return connection for the antenna current thus having an additional effect, particularly on the impedance seen by the feed line.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] When an electromagnetic wave strikes a plane surface such as the ground, part of the wave is transmitted into the ground and part of it is reflected, according to the Fresnel coefficients.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] If the ground is a very good conductor then almost all of the wave is reflected (180° out of phase), whereas a ground modeled as a (lossy) dielectric can absorb a large amount of the wave's power.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The power remaining in the reflected wave, and the phase shift upon reflection, strongly depend on the wave's angle of incidence and polarization.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The dielectric constant and conductivity (or simply the complex dielectric constant) is dependent on the soil type and is a function of frequency.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] At lower mediumwave frequencies the ground acts mainly as a good conductor, which AM broadcast (0.5–1.7 MHz) antennas depend on.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] At frequencies between 3–30 MHz, a large portion of the energy from a horizontally polarized antenna reflects off the ground, with almost total reflection at the grazing angles important for ground wave propagation.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] That reflected wave, with its phase reversed, can either cancel or reinforce the direct wave, depending on the antenna height in wavelengths and elevation angle (for a sky wave).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, vertically polarized radiation is not well reflected by the ground except at grazing incidence or over very highly conducting surfaces such as sea water.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] However the grazing angle reflection important for ground wave propagation, using vertical polarization, is *in phase* with the direct wave, providing a boost of up to 6 dB, as is detailed below.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] At VHF and above (> 30 MHz) the ground becomes a poorer reflector.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] However, for shortwave frequencies, especially below ~15 MHz, it remains a good reflector especially for horizontal polarization and grazing angles of incidence.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] That is important as these higher frequencies usually depend on horizontal line-of-sight propagation (except for satellite communications), the ground then behaving almost as a mirror.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] The net quality of a ground reflection depends on the topography of the surface.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] When the irregularities of the surface are much smaller than the wavelength, the dominant regime is that of specular reflection, and the receiver sees both the real antenna and an image of the antenna under the ground due to reflection.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] But if the ground has irregularities not small compared to the wavelength, reflections will not be coherent but shifted by random phases.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] With shorter wavelengths (higher frequencies), this is generally the case.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] Whenever both the receiving or transmitting antenna are placed at significant heights above the ground (relative to the wavelength), waves reflected specularly by the ground will travel a longer distance than direct waves, inducing a phase shift which can sometimes be significant.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p01] When a sky wave is launched by such an antenna, that phase shift is always significant unless the antenna is very close to the ground (compared to the wavelength).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] The flow of current in wire antennas is identical to the solution of counter-propagating waves in a single conductor transmission line, which can be solved using the telegrapher's equations.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Unlike transmission lines, currents in antennas contribute power to the radiated part electromagnetic field, which can be modeled using radiation resistance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] The combination of the incident and reflected wave, just as in a transmission line, forms a standing wave with a current node at the conductor's end, and a voltage node one-quarter wavelength from the end (if the element is at least that long).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] In a *resonant antenna*, the feedpoint of the antenna is at one of those voltage nodes.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Due to discrepancies from the simplified version of the transmission line model, the voltage one quarter wavelength from the current node is not exactly zero, but it is near a minimum, and small compared to the much larger voltage at the conductor's end.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Hence, a feed point matching the antenna at that spot requires a relatively small voltage but large current (the currents from the two waves add in-phase there), thus a relatively low feedpoint impedance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Feeding the antenna at other points involves a large voltage, thus a large impedance, and usually one that is primarily reactive (low power factor), which is a terrible impedance match to available transmission lines.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, it is usually desired for an antenna to operate as a resonant element with each conductor having a length of one quarter wavelength (or any other odd multiples of a quarter wavelength).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, a half-wave dipole has two such elements (one connected to each conductor of a balanced transmission line) about one quarter wavelength long.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Depending on the conductors' diameters, a small deviation from this length is adopted in order to reach the point where the antenna current and the (small) feedpoint voltage are exactly in phase.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Then the antenna presents a purely resistive impedance, and ideally one close to the characteristic impedance of an available transmission line.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Despite these useful properties, resonant antennas have the disadvantage that they achieve resonance (purely resistive feedpoint impedance) only at a fundamental frequency, and perhaps some of its harmonics, and the feedpoint resistance is larger at higher-order resonances.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, resonant antennas can only achieve their good performance within a limited bandwidth, depending on the Q at the resonance.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] The electric and magnetic fields emanating from a driven antenna element will generally affect the voltages and currents in nearby antennas, antenna elements, or other conductors.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] This is particularly true when the affected conductor is a resonant element (multiple of half-wavelengths in length) at about the same frequency, as is the case where the conductors are all part of the same active or passive antenna array.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Thus using the mutual impedances calculated for a specific geometry, one can solve for the radiation pattern of a Yagi–Uda antenna or the currents and voltages for each element of a phased array.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Such an analysis can also describe in detail reflection of radio waves by a ground plane or by a corner reflector and their effect on the impedance (and radiation pattern) of an antenna in its vicinity.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Often such near-field interactions are undesired and pernicious.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Currents in random metal objects near a transmitting antenna will often be in poor conductors, causing loss of RF power in addition to unpredictably altering the characteristics of the antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] By careful design, it is possible to reduce the electrical interaction between nearby conductors.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, the 90 degree angle in between the two dipoles composing the turnstile antenna ensures no interaction between these, allowing these to be driven independently (but actually with the same signal in quadrature phases in the turnstile antenna design).
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Antennas can be classified by operating principles or by their application.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] Different authorities placed antennas in narrower or broader categories.
[src:ground-station-systems/antenna-radio-p02] These antenna types and others are summarized in greater detail in the overview article, Antenna types, as well as in each of the linked articles in the list above, and in even more detail in articles which those link to.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The **NASA Deep Space Network** (**DSN**) is a worldwide network of spacecraft communication ground segment facilities, located in the United States (California), Spain (Madrid), and Australia (Canberra), that supports NASA's interplanetary spacecraft missions.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] It also performs radio and radar astronomy observations for the exploration of the Solar System and the universe, and supports selected Earth-orbiting missions.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] DSN is part of the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] DSN currently consists of three deep-space communications facilities located such that a distant spacecraft is always in view of at least one station.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Each facility is situated in semi-mountainous, bowl-shaped terrain to help shield against radio frequency interference.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The strategic placement of the stations permits constant observation of spacecraft as the Earth rotates, which helps to make the DSN the largest and most sensitive scientific telecommunications system in the world.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN supports NASA's contribution to the scientific investigation of the Solar System: It provides a two-way communications link that guides and controls various NASA uncrewed interplanetary space probes, and brings back the images and new scientific information these probes collect.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] All DSN antennas are steerable, high-gain, parabolic reflector antennas.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Other countries and organizations also run deep space networks.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN operates according to the standards of the Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems, as do most other deep space networks, and hence the DSN is able to inter-operate with the networks of other space agencies.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] These include the Soviet Deep Space Network, the Chinese Deep Space Network, the Indian Deep Space Network, the Japanese Deep Space Network, and the ESTRACK of the European Space Agency.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] These agencies often cooperate for better mission coverage.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In particular, DSN has a cross-support agreement with ESA that allows mutual use of both networks for more effectiveness and reduced risk.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In addition, radio astronomy facilities, such as the Parkes Observatory, the Green Bank Telescope, and the Very Large Array, are sometimes used to supplement the antennas of the DSN.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The antennas at all three DSN Complexes communicate directly with the Deep Space Operations Center (also known as Deep Space Network operations control center) located at the JPL facilities in Pasadena, California.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In the early years, the operations control center did not have a permanent facility.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] It was a provisional setup with numerous desks and phones installed in a large room near the computers used to calculate orbits.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In July 1961, NASA started the construction of the permanent facility, Space Flight Operations Facility (SFOF).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The facility was completed in October 1963 and dedicated on May 14, 1964.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In the initial setup of the SFOF, there were 31 consoles, 100 closed-circuit television cameras, and more than 200 television displays to support Ranger 6 to Ranger 9 and Mariner 4.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Currently, the operations center personnel at SFOF monitor and direct operations, and oversee the quality of spacecraft telemetry and navigation data delivered to network users.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In addition to the DSN complexes and the operations center, a ground communications facility provides communications that link the three complexes to the operations center at JPL, to space flight control centers in the United States and overseas, and to scientists around the world.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Tracking vehicles in deep space is quite different from tracking missions in low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Deep space missions are visible for long periods of time from a large portion of the Earth's surface, and so require few stations (the DSN has only three main sites).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] These few stations, however, require huge antennas, ultra-sensitive receivers, and powerful transmitters in order to transmit and receive over the vast distances involved.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Deep space is defined in several different ways.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The International Telecommunication Union, which sets aside various frequency bands for deep space and near Earth use, defines "deep space" to start at a distance of 2 million km (1.2 million mi) from the Earth's surface.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The NASA Deep Space Network can both send and receive in all of the ITU deep space bands—S-band (2 GHz), X-band (8 GHz), and Ka-band (32 GHz).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Frequency usage has in general moved upward over the life of the DSN, as higher frequencies have higher gain for the same size antenna, and the deep space bands are wider, so more data can be returned.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] However, higher frequencies also need more accurate pointing (on the spacecraft) and more precise antenna surfaces (on Earth), so improvements in both spacecraft and the DSN were required to move to higher bands.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Early missions used S-band for both uplink and downlink.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Viking (1975) had X-band as an experiment, and Voyager (1977) was the first to use it operationally.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Similarly, Mars Observer (1994) carried a Ka-band experiment, Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter (2005) had a Ka-band demo, and Kepler (2009) was the first mission to use Ka-band as the primary downlink.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] However, not all space missions can use these bands.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The Moon, the Earth-moon Lagrange points, and the Earth–Sun Lagrangian points L1 and L2 are all closer than 2 million km from Earth (distances are here), so they are considered near space and cannot use the ITU's deep space bands.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Missions at these locations that need high data rates must therefore use the "near space" K band (27 GHz).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Since NASA has several such missions (such as the James Webb Space Telescope and the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter), they have enhanced the Deep Space Network to receive (but not transmit) at these frequencies as well.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN is also pursuing optical deep space communication, offering greater communication speeds at the cost of susceptibility to weather and the need for extremely precise pointing of the spacecraft.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] This technology is working in prototype form.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The forerunner of the DSN was established in January 1958, when JPL, then under contract to the US Army, deployed portable radio tracking stations in Nigeria, Singapore, and California to receive telemetry and plot the orbit of the Army-launched Explorer 1, the first successful US satellite.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] NASA was officially established on October 1, 1958, to consolidate the separately developing space-exploration programs of the US Army, US Navy, and US Air Force into one civilian organization.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] On December 3, 1958, JPL was transferred from the US Army to NASA and given responsibility for the design and execution of lunar and planetary exploration programs using remotely controlled spacecraft.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN was given responsibility for its own research, development, and operation in support of all of its users.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Under this concept, it has become a world leader in the development of low-noise receivers; large parabolic-dish antennas; tracking, telemetry, and command systems; digital signal processing; and deep space navigation.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The Deep Space Network formally announced its intention to send missions into deep space on Christmas Eve 1963; it has remained in continuous operation in one capacity or another ever since.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The largest antennas of the DSN are often called on during spacecraft emergencies.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Almost all spacecraft are designed so normal operation can be conducted on the smaller (and more economical) antennas of the DSN, but during an emergency the use of the largest antennas is crucial.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] This is because a troubled spacecraft may be forced to use less than its normal transmitter power, attitude control problems may preclude the use of high-gain antennas, and recovering every bit of telemetry is critical to assessing the health of the spacecraft and planning the recovery.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] While Apollo was also a US mission, DSN provides this emergency service to other space agencies as well, in a spirit of inter-agency and international cooperation.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] For example, the recovery of the Solar and Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO) mission of the European Space Agency (ESA) would not have been possible without the use of the largest DSN facilities.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Although normally tasked with tracking uncrewed spacecraft, the Deep Space Network (DSN) also contributed to the communication and tracking of Apollo missions to the Moon, although primary responsibility was held by the Manned Space Flight Network (MSFN).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN designed the MSFN stations for lunar communication and provided a second antenna at each MSFN site (the MSFN sites were near the DSN sites for just this reason).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Two antennas at each site were needed both for redundancy and because the beam widths of the large antennas needed were too small to encompass both the lunar orbiter and the lander at the same time.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] DSN also supplied some larger antennas as needed, in particular for television broadcasts from the Moon, and emergency communications such as Apollo 13.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The details of this cooperation and operation are available in a two-volume technical report from JPL.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The network is a NASA facility and is managed and operated for NASA by JPL, which is part of the California Institute of Technology (Caltech).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The Interplanetary Network Directorate (IND) manages the program within JPL and is charged with the development and operation of it.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The IND is considered to be JPL's focal point for all matters relating to telecommunications, interplanetary navigation, information systems, information technology, computing, software engineering, and other relevant technologies.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] While the IND is best known for its duties relating to the Deep Space Network, the organization also maintains the JPL Advanced Multi-Mission Operations System (AMMOS) and JPL's Institutional Computing and Information Services (ICIS).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The facilities in Spain and Australia are jointly owned and operated in conjunction with that government's scientific institutions.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Similarly, in Spain, "Ingenieria de Sistemas para la Defensa de España S.A.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] (ISDEFE), a wholly owned subsidiary of the Instituto Nacional de Técnica Aeroespacial (INTA) and a part of the Spanish Department of Defense, operates and maintains the Madrid Deep Space Communications Complex (Madrid)".
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Peraton (formerly Harris Corporation) is under contract to JPL for the DSN's operations and maintenance.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Peraton has responsibility for managing the Goldstone complex, operating the DSOC, and for DSN operations, mission planning, operations engineering, and logistics.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Each complex consists of at least four deep space terminals equipped with ultra-sensitive receiving systems and large parabolic-dish antennas.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Five of the 34-meter (112 ft) beam waveguide antennas were added to the system in the late 1990s.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Three were located at Goldstone, and one each at Canberra and Madrid.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] A second 34-meter (112 ft) beam waveguide antenna (the network's sixth) was completed at the Madrid complex in 2004.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In order to meet the current and future needs of deep space communication services, a number of new Deep Space Station antennas had to be built at the existing Deep Space Network sites.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] At the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex the first of these was completed in October 2014 (DSS35), with a second becoming operational in October 2016 (DSS36).
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] A new 34-meter dish (DSS53) became operational at the Madrid complex in February 2022.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The 70 meter antennas are aging and more difficult to maintain than the modern BWG antennas.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Therefore in 2012 NASA announced a plan to decommission all three of them and replace them with arrayed 34-meter BWG antennas.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Each of these new antennas would be upgraded to have X-band uplink capabilities and both X and Ka-band downlink capabilities.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] However by 2021, NASA decided instead to do a complete refurbishment of all 70-meter antennas, requiring taking them offline for months at a time.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] These refurbished antennas were expected to serve for decades to come.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The general capabilities of the DSN have not substantially changed since the beginning of the Voyager Interstellar Mission in the early 1990s.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] However, many advancements in digital signal processing, arraying and error correction have been adopted by the DSN.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN array currently available since the *Galileo* mission can link the 70-meter (230 ft) dish antenna at the Deep Space Network complex in Goldstone, California, with an identical antenna located in Australia, in addition to two 34-meter (112 ft) antennas at the Canberra complex.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The California and Australia sites were used concurrently to pick up communications with *Galileo*.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Arraying of antennas within the three DSN locations is also used.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] For example, a 70-meter (230 ft) dish antenna can be arrayed with a 34-meter dish.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] For especially vital missions, like *Voyager 2*, non-DSN facilities normally used for radio astronomy can be added to the array.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In particular, the Canberra 70-meter (230 ft) dish can be arrayed with the Parkes Radio Telescope in Australia; and the Goldstone 70-meter dish can be arrayed with the Very Large Array of antennas in New Mexico.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Also, two or more 34-meter (112 ft) dishes at one DSN location are commonly arrayed together.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] All the stations are remotely operated from a centralized Signal Processing Center at each complex.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] These Centers house the electronic subsystems that point and control the antennas, receive and process the telemetry data, transmit commands, and generate the spacecraft navigation data.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Once the data are processed at the complexes, they are transmitted to JPL for further processing and for distribution to science teams over a modern communications network.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Especially at Mars, there are often many spacecraft within the beam width of an antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] For operational efficiency, a single antenna can receive signals from multiple spacecraft at the same time.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] This capability is called **Multiple Spacecraft Per Aperture**, or **MSPA**.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Currently, the DSN can receive up to 4 spacecraft signals at the same time, or MSPA-4.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] However, apertures cannot currently be shared for uplink.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] When two or more high-power carriers are used simultaneously, very high order intermodulation products fall in the receiver bands, causing interference to the much (25 orders of magnitude) weaker received signals.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Therefore, only one spacecraft at a time can get an uplink, though up to 4 can be received.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] There are a number of limitations to the current DSN, and a number of challenges going forward.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Most of these are outlined in a 2023 Audit of NASA's Deep Space Network performed by NASA's Office of Inspector General.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Because of capacity limits on the DSN, new spacecraft intended for missions beyond geocentric orbits are being equipped to use the beacon mode service, which allows such missions to operate without the DSN most of the time.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] In addition, NASA is creating a network of Lunar Exploration Ground Sites to offload much of the lunar and Artemis mission needs from the DSN.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN forms one portion of the radio sciences experiment included on most deep space missions, where radio links between spacecraft and Earth are used to investigate planetary science, space physics and fundamental physics.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The experiments include radio occultations, gravity field determination and celestial mechanics, bistatic scattering, doppler wind experiments, solar corona characterization, and tests of fundamental physics.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] For example, the Deep Space Network forms one component of the gravity science experiment on *Juno*.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] This includes special communication hardware on Juno and uses its communication system.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] The DSN radiates a Ka-band uplink, which is picked up by *Juno*'s Ka-Band communication system and then processed by a special communication box called KaTS, and then this new signal is sent back the DSN.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] This allows the velocity of the spacecraft over time to be determined with a level of precision that allows a more accurate determination of the gravity field at planet Jupiter.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] Another radio science experiment is REX on the *New Horizons* spacecraft to Pluto-Charon.
[src:ground-station-systems/deep-space-network] REX received a signal from Earth as it was occulted by Pluto, to take various measurements of that system of bodies.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A **ground station**, **Earth station**, or **Earth terminal** is a terrestrial radio station designed for extraplanetary telecommunication with spacecraft (constituting part of the ground segment of the spacecraft system), or reception of radio waves from astronomical radio sources.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Ground stations may be located either on the surface of the Earth, or in its atmosphere.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Earth stations communicate with spacecraft by transmitting and receiving radio waves in the super high frequency (SHF) or extremely high frequency (EHF) bands (e.g. microwaves), or in the optical bands for laser communication (then called Optical Ground Station, OGS).
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] When a ground station successfully transmits radio waves to a spacecraft (or vice versa), it establishes a telecommunications link.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A principal telecommunications device of the ground station is the parabolic antenna.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Ground stations may have either a fixed or itinerant position.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Article 1 § III of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) Radio Regulations describes various types of stationary and mobile ground stations, and their interrelationships.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Specialized **satellite Earth stations** or **satellite tracking stations** are used to telecommunicate with satellites — chiefly communications satellites.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Other ground stations communicate with crewed space stations or uncrewed space probes.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A ground station that primarily receives telemetry data, or that follows space missions, or satellites not in geostationary orbit, is called a **ground tracking station**, or **space tracking station**, or simply a **tracking station**.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] When a spacecraft or satellite is within a ground station's line of sight, the station is said to have a *view* of the spacecraft (see *pass*).
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A spacecraft can communicate with more than one ground station at a time.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A pair of ground stations are said to have a spacecraft in *mutual view* when the stations share simultaneous, unobstructed, line-of-sight contact with the spacecraft.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A *telecommunications port* — or, more commonly, *teleport* — is a satellite ground station that functions as a hub connecting a satellite or geocentric orbital network with a terrestrial telecommunications network, such as the Internet.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Teleports may provide various broadcasting services among other telecommunications functions, such as uploading computer programs or issuing commands over an uplink to a satellite.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] In May 1984, the Dallas/Fort Worth Teleport became the first American teleport to commence operation.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] In Federal Standard 1037C, the United States General Services Administration defined an *Earth terminal complex* as the assemblage of equipment and facilities necessary to integrate an Earth terminal (ground station) into a telecommunications network.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] FS-1037C has since been subsumed by the ATIS Telecom Glossary, which is maintained by the Alliance for Telecommunications Industry Solutions (ATIS), an international, business-oriented, non-governmental organization.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] The Telecommunications Industry Association also acknowledges this definition.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] The ITU Radiocommunication Sector (ITU-R), a division of the International Telecommunication Union, codifies international standards agreed-upon through multinational discourse.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] From 1927 to 1932, the International Consultative Committee for Radio administered standards and regulations now governed by the ITU-R.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] In addition to the body of standards defined by the ITU-R, each major satellite operator provides technical requirements and standards that ground stations must meet in order to communicate with the operator's satellites.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] For example, Intelsat publishes the Intelsat Earth Station Standards (IESS) which, among other things, classifies ground stations by the capabilities of their parabolic antennas, and pre-approves certain antenna models.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] Eutelsat publishes similar standards and requirements, such as the Eutelsat Earth Station Standards (EESS).
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] The Interagency Operations Advisory Group offers a Service Catalog describing standard services, Spacecraft Emergency Cross Support Standard, and Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems data standards.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] The Teleport (originally called a *Telecommunications Satellite Park*) innovation was conceived and developed by Joseph Milano in 1976 as part of a National Research Council study entitled, *Telecommunications for Metropolitan Areas: Near-Term Needs and Opportunities*.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A network of ground stations is a group of stations located to support spacecraft communication, tracking, or both.
[src:ground-station-systems/ground-station] A network is established to provide dedicated support to a specific mission, function, program or organization.
[src:ground-station-systems/mission-control-center] control rooms in Russia and in the United States.
[src:ground-station-systems/mission-control-center] A **mission control center** (**MCC**, sometimes called a **flight control center** or **operations center**) is a facility that manages space flights, usually from the point of launch until landing or the end of the mission.
[src:ground-station-systems/mission-control-center] It is part of the ground segment of spacecraft operations.
[src:ground-station-systems/mission-control-center] A staff of flight controllers and other support personnel monitor all aspects of the mission using telemetry, and send commands to the vehicle using ground stations.
[src:ground-station-systems/mission-control-center] Personnel supporting the mission from an MCC can include representatives of the attitude control system, power, propulsion, thermal, attitude dynamics, orbital operations and other subsystem disciplines.
[src:ground-station-systems/mission-control-center] The training for these missions usually falls under the responsibility of the flight controllers, typically including extensive rehearsals in the MCC.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:ground-station-systems/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] In a telecommunications network, a **link** is a communication channel that connects two or more devices for the purpose of data transmission.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] The link may be a dedicated physical link or a virtual circuit that uses one or more physical links or shares a physical link with other telecommunications links.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] A telecommunications link is generally based on one of several types of information transmission paths such as those provided by communication satellites, terrestrial radio communications infrastructure (a **radio link**) and computer networks to connect two or more points.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] The term *link* is widely used in computer networking to refer to the communications facilities that connect nodes of a network.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] A point-to-point link is a dedicated link that connects exactly two communication facilities (e.g., two nodes of a network, an intercom station at an entryway with a single internal intercom station, a radio path between two points, etc.).
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] Broadcast links connect two or more nodes and support *broadcast transmission*, where one node can transmit so that all other nodes can receive the same transmission.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] A layer-1 Network segment in Ethernet is an example of this.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] Also known as a *multidrop* link, a multipoint link is a link that connects *two or more* nodes.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] Also known as general topology networks, these include ATM and Frame Relay links, as well as X.25 networks when used as links for a network-layer protocol like IP.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] Unlike broadcast links, there is no mechanism to efficiently send a single message to all other nodes without copying and retransmitting the message.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] A point-to-multipoint link (or simply a *multipoint*) is a specific type of multipoint link which consists of a central connection endpoint (CE) that is connected to multiple peripheral CEs.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] All of the peripheral CEs receive any transmission of data that originates from the central CE while any transmission of data that originates from any of the peripheral CEs is only received by the central CE.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] Links are often referred to by terms that refer to the ownership or accessibility of the link.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] A **forward link** is the link from a fixed location (e.g., a base station) to a mobile user.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] If the link includes a communications relay satellite, the forward link will consist of both an uplink (base station to satellite) and a downlink (satellite to mobile user).
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] The **reverse link** (sometimes called a *return channel*) is the link from a mobile user to a fixed base station.
[src:ground-station-systems/uplink] If the link includes a communications relay satellite, the reverse link will consist of both an uplink (mobile station to satellite) and a downlink (satellite to base station) which together constitute a half hop.
